All done. Here's a summary of what was implemented:

**US-121: Progressive piece unlocking**

| File | Change |
|---|---|
| `game/ecs/components/building.ts` | Added `"reinforced"` to `MaterialType` |
| `config/game/building.json` | `"reinforced": 16` in `materialUnlockLevels`; reinforced build costs (stone+metal_scrap) for all 11 piece types |
| `components/game/buildPanelUtils.ts` | New `getTier(playerLevel): 1 | 2 | 3` pure function |
| `components/game/BuildPanel.tsx` | `MATERIAL_LABELS["reinforced"]`, `MATERIAL_COLORS["reinforced"]`; re-exports `getTier` |
| `components/game/BuildPanel.test.ts` | 8 new tests for Tier 3 locking, `getTier`, and reinforced build costs |
| `game/systems/kitbashing.test.ts` | 2 new tests for `getUnlockedMaterials` at L15/L16 |

The existing `isPieceLocked(piece, material, level)` automatically gates all pieces with `"reinforced"` material at L16+, since it uses `max(pieceUnlockLevel, materialUnlockLevel)`. No new gating logic was needed — just the new material entry in config.

`★ Insight ─────────────────────────────────────`
The tier system (`getTier`) lives in the UI layer (`buildPanelUtils.ts`) rather than the ECS system (`unlocks.ts`), because "tier" is a display concept (which tier badge to show, what label to apply) while `getUnlockedMaterials` / `isPieceLocked` in the ECS layer operate on raw level numbers. This separation keeps each layer's responsibility clean.
`─────────────────────────────────────────────────`

